{"id":"1905.03575","submitter":"Mario Bernal Prof.","authors":"R. Seraide, M. A. Bernal, G. Brunetto, U. de Giovannini, A. Rubio","title":"A TDDFT-based Study on the Proton-DNA Collision","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1021/acs.jpcb.7b04934","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.bio-ph physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The interaction of heavy charged particles with DNA is of interest for\nseveral areas, from hadrontherapy to aero-space industry. In this paper, a\nTD-DFT study on the interaction of a 4 keV proton with an isolated DNA base\npair was carried out. Ehrenfest dynamics was used to study the evolution of the\nsystem during and after the proton impact up to about 193 fs. This time was\nlong enough to observe the dissociation of the target, which occurs between\n80-100 fs. The effect of base pair linking to the DNA double helix was emulated\nby fixing the four O3' atoms responsible for the attachment. The base pair\ntends to dissociate into its main components, namely the phosphate groups,\nsugars and nitrogenous bases. A central impact with energy transfer of 17.9 eV\nonly produces base damage while keeping the backbone intact. An impact on a\nphosphate group with energy transfer of about 60 eV leads to backbone break at\nthat site together with base damage, while the opposite backbone site integrity\nis kept is this situation. As the whole system is perturbed during such a\ncollision, no atom remains passive. These results suggest that base damage\naccompanies all backbone breaks since hydrogen bonds that keep bases together\nare much weaker that those between the other components of the DNA.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 9 May 2019 12:39:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-10"}
